Appendix D: Tensor Network Representations for Non-Commutative Inference Models

D.1 Matrix Product States (MPS)

For a 1D chain of $N$ sites with local dimension $d$, an MPS is
|\psi\rangle = \sum_{s_1,\dots,s_N} \operatorname{Tr}(A_1^{s_1} \cdots A_N^{s_N}) |s_1\cdots s_N\rangle,


where each $A_i^{s}$ is a $D \times D$ matrix (bond dimension $D$). Expectation values of local observables can be computed efficiently using transfer matrices.

D.2 Representing States on C*-Algebras

If $\mathcal{A} = \bigotimes_{i=1}^N M_d(\mathbb{C})$, a state can be represented by a density matrix $\rho$ of size $d^N$. For large $N$, MPS provide an efficient parametrization: $\rho = \operatorname{Tr}_{\text{anc}}(|\Psi\rangle\langle\Psi|)$ where $|\Psi\rangle$ is an MPS on an enlarged space including ancillas.

D.3 Bayesian Update with Tensor Networks

Given a prior MPS $\rho$ and a likelihood channel $\Phi$ (which may be local), the Petz map $\mathcal{P}_{\omega,\Phi}$ can be implemented using tensor network techniques such as TEBD (time-evolving block decimation) or DMRG (density matrix renormalization group). The update corresponds to applying a local operator and then truncating the bond dimension to keep the representation manageable.

D.4 Complexity

MPS representations allow efficient computation of expectation values, relative entropies, and gradient flows, provided the bond dimension remains $O(\text{poly}(N))$. This connects the abstract theory to practical algorithms for large-scale non-commutative inference.

